In utils.c

`static int
write_file_and_check_fs_type (const char *file, const char *data, size_t len, unsigned int type, const char *type_name,
                              libcrun_error_t *err)
{
  int ret;
  struct statfs sfs;
  cleanup_close int fd = -1;

  fd = open (file, O_WRONLY | O_CLOEXEC);
  if (UNLIKELY (fd < 0))
    return crun_make_error (err, errno, "open file `%s`", file);

  ret = fstatfs (fd, &sfs);
  if (UNLIKELY (ret < 0))
    return crun_make_error (err, errno, "statfs `%s`", file);

  if (sfs.f_type != type)
    return crun_make_error (err, 0, "the file `%s` is not on file system type `%s`", file, type_name);

  **ret = TEMP_FAILURE_RETRY (write (fd, data, len));
  if (UNLIKELY (ret < 0))
    return crun_make_error (err, errno, "write file `%s`", file);**

  return 0;
}

int
set_selinux_exec_label (const char *label, libcrun_error_t *err)
{
  int ret;

  ret = libcrun_is_selinux_enabled (err);
  if (UNLIKELY (ret < 0))
    return ret;

  if (ret)
    {
      **ret = write_file_and_check_fs_type ("/proc/thread-self/attr/exec", label, strlen (label), PROC_SUPER_MAGIC,
                                          "procfs", err);
      if (UNLIKELY (ret < 0))
        return ret;**
    }
  return 0;
}
`
This UNLIKELY return from write_file_and_check_fs_type is kicking off an error on TEMP_FAILURE_RETRY

$ ls -laZ /proc/thread-self/attr/exec 
-rw-rw-rw-. 1 chaasmadmin chaasmadmin sysadm_u:sysadm_r:sysadm_t:s0-s0:c0.c1023 0 Jan 29 22:01 /proc/thread-self/attr/exec

The file is empty.

No new typebounds or NoNewPrivileges:

$ seinfo --typebounds
Typebounds: 0

$ grep NoNewPrivs /proc/self/status
NoNewPrivs:	0

Yes, the container_t domain was missing a number of attributes and types. Now....

$ seinfo -tcontainer_t -x

Types: 1
   type container_t alias svirt_lxc_net_t, can_dump_kernel, can_receive_kernel_messages, corenet_unconfined_type, domain, mcs_constrained_type, process_user_target, container_domain, container_net_domain, ifplugd_typeattr_1, pcmcia_typeattr_1, sandbox_net_domain, kernel_system_state_reader, syslog_client_type, svirt_sandbox_domain;

The current work has cgroupv2 and cgroupfs working for runc and crun with container-selinux (able to build bootstrapped container images with RUN commands) on Ubuntu 20.04.1 LTS. The current issue is systemd-cgroupfs which always errors sd-bus call failed: permission denied on crun and a related error in runc with setenforce 1. A setenforce 0 allows the build of a container from a Dockerfile to work for both runtimes, and no AVCs are displayed. After putting dbus and systemd policy code under the microscope, I believe the version of refpolicy (20190201-8) may not be in sync with the newer systemd/dbus changes and updating that to the current 20210203 policy may be necessary to better integrate the init, dbus, and systemd policies.

In order to get where I am now, I had to remove the refpolicy virt policy in Ubuntu, pull the virt policy source from fedora, , and add the following to the fedora virt.te (plus the necessary missing interfaces in virt.if):
